It is a prerequisite to determine rpore and ε* in order to use this relation to compute εpore. While rpore is determined from retention of PEG 200, there is no empirical method to determine ε*. Bowen et al. [42] assumed that ε* may reach the high-frequency limit of the dielectric constant of water. Therefore, they used ε* = 6 to calculate εpore of the Desal-DK membrane. Hussain et al. [43] determined the experimental rejection of NaCl at the isoelectric point and determined ε* by fitting the experimental rejection data with modelled rejection data where steric and dielectric exclusion was considered to be the only exclusion pa­rameters. They reported for Desal-HL membrane ε* = 34 (when Stokes radius is used). The value of ε* originates from the affinity of water molecules with the pore walls [6]. Hence, the nature and content of the functional groups at the pore walls are likely to play a dictating role for the ε* of a given membrane. Similar to our previous work [5], we assumed the value of ε* changes only with the TMC concentration. Double minimization with the following objective function was used to determine ε* and cx simultaneously.

